column3: Chronic Absenteeism (20+ days) (<90%)
column24: The percentage of students present less than 90% of school days in a school year
column25: NYC Department of Education
column26: In the past few years, NYC DOE has had some consistency issues in their public reporting of attendance. In order to ensure that the numbers in the Social Indicators Report matches their publicly reported numbers, they have changed the metric to <90% of days for students in all districts from what it is now, which is the percentage of students absent 20+ days in districts 1-32.

column3: Four-Year College Readiness
column24: The percentage of students are college ready according to the the College Readiness Index (CRI).The College Readiness Index (CRI) is calculated by the NYC Department of Education and includes students who meet CUNY’s remediation standards, which are currently defined as: (1) graduated by August with a Regents diploma, (2) earned a 75+ on the English Regents exam, or scored 480+ on the Critical Reading SAT, or scored a 20+ on the ACT English, or scored a 70+ on the CUNY Reading Assessment and a 56+ on the CUNY Writing Assessment, and (3) scored an 80+ on a Math Regents, or 70+ on a Common Core Algebra or Geometry Regents and completed coursework in Algebra II/Trigonometry or higher, or scored 480+ on the Math SAT, or scored a 20+ on the ACT Math, or scored a 40+ on the CUNY Math Assessment, or scored an 80+ on the PBAT and completed required coursework.
column25: NYC Department of Education

column3: Number of NYC Public School Students Attaining Associate's or Bachelor's Degrees
column24: The percentage of NYC DOE on-time high school graduates who enrolled and graduated from college with an Associate’s or Bachelor’s degree within six years. (Year indicates high school graduation year.)
column25: NYC Department of Education
column26: DOE does not have metrics on the number of New York City public school students attaining associate’s or bachelor’s degrees. Unlike other metrics in this report, the college performance metrics rely on data that must be obtained from an outside source.

column3: Rental Housing Vacancy Rate
column24: The net rental vacancy rate is calculated by dividing the number of vacant, habitable, and available-for-rent units by the number of renter-occupied units plus vacant, habitable, and available for-rent units. This calculation excludes housing units in group quarters, such as hospitals, jails, mental institutions, and college dormitories, as well as units that are rented but not occupied and vacant units that are in such poor condition that they are not habitable.
column25: HPD : Selected Initial Findings of the 2017 New York City Housing and Vacancy Survey

column3: Rental Housing Vacancy Rate
column24: The net rental vacancy rate is calculated by dividing the number of vacant, habitable, and available-for-rent units by the number of renter-occupied units plus vacant, habitable, and available for-rent units. This calculation excludes housing units in group quarters, such as hospitals, jails, mental institutions, and college dormitories, as well as units that are rented but not occupied and vacant units that are in such poor condition that they are not habitable.
column25: HPD : Selected Initial Findings of the 2017 New York City Housing and Vacancy Survey

column3: Homeless: Average System Length of Stay
column24: For Families with Children and Adult Families, this indicator measures the average number of days families spend in shelter, excluding late arrival facilities, from their first date of application (families who leave the DHS shelter system for more than 30 days are considered new applicants). For Single Adults, this indicator measures the average number of days an adult has spent in the DHS shelter services system during the reporting period (including non-consecutive days spent in shelters, excluding clients in Safe Havens and Veteran short-term housing).
column25: NYC Department of Homeless Services, CARES data system
column26: 2011 Marks the end of the Advantage Program.

column3: Serious Housing Code Violations (per 1,000 privately owned rental units)
column24: The New York City Department of Housing Preservation and Development investigates housing code complaints from tenants and issues code violations if housing inspections reveal problems. Serious Housing Code Violations are class C (immediately hazardous). The New York City Housing Authority has a parallel process for recording and inspecting housing violations within public housing. NYCHA violations are not included in this indicator.
column25: New York City Department of Housing Preservation and Development, New York City Department of Finance Final Tax Roll File, New York City Housing Authority, NYU Furman Center
